<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-291-555  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 291 555.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Jan 30 1989 n1104* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Single chip solution to LIM 4.0 from Chips andamp; Tech. (Chips andamp;Technologies Inc.) (Lotus-Intel-Microsoft Expanded MemorySpecification 4.0) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chips and Technologies Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    CHPS.andO;Product:   Chips and Technologies EMS MapperChip (Semiconductor device)EMS 4.0 (Computer program) (usage).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionIntegrated CircuitsMemoryMS-DOS.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SINGLE CHIP SOLUTION TO LIM 4.0 FROM CHIPS andamp; TECH In what looks like anotherlifeline for MS-DOS and another blow to OS/2, a very low-cost solution to theproblem of expanding memory beyond the 640Kb limit of MS-DOS is nowavailable.andP;  Designers wanting to implement the Lotus-Intel-Microsoft ExpandedMemory Specification 4.0 in their AT-alikes can now do so with a single chiprather than taking up one of the expansion slots and using add-in boards,courtesy of the folks at Chips andamp; Technologies Inc, San Jose.andP;  The companyoffers the EMS Mapper chip - that name ain't going to go too down well withUnisys Corp - at a mere $12.50 in OEM volumes - which translates to anend-user price of about $40 against hundreds of dollars for the presentsolution, according to Microbytes.andP;  Called the 82C631, the chip has two banksof 64 registers that access the expanded memory and can switch from one bankto another with one input-output instruction and requires no wait states whenused with CPU clock speeds of up to 16MHz.andP;  The chip also contains asoftware-controllable enable-disable feature, so that memory above 640Kb canbe used either as expanded or extended memory.andP;  Four of the chips can bestacked together for a maximum of eight register banks, to support a maximumof eight tasks.andP;  Volume is promised for the second quarter, and the companysays that at least two of its major OEM customers have already gone for thechip - it won't say which, but Apricot Computers Plc, Zenith Data, DellComputer and Tandy Corp are big Chips andamp; Technologies customers.andO;</TEXT></DOC>